A heating curve is a diagram that represents the different changes of state that a substance can experience, with the temperature showing in the vertical axis and heat on the horizontal axis. The heating curves have inclined lines as well as horizontal lines. The horizontal lines represent phase transitions, such as solid to liquid or liquid to solid. The inclined lines represent warming up process, is the incline goes up, and cooling down processes if the line points down. When heat is added to the substance, we will have heating curves, whereas if heat is removed we will have cooling curves. For low temperatures, the solid phase will exist, whereas for higher temperatures liquids and vapor will exist. In a phase transition, the two phases involved in the transition will coexist. For example, when ice melts, we will have at the same time ice and water in contact. In a similar way, when water steams, we will have liquid and solid in contact. The temperature axis in the temperature curves allows us to identify the temperature for a phase transition. For example, ice will melt at 0$^{\circ}C$ and water will boil at 100$^{\circ}C$.
